Extra virgin olive oil is a virgin olive oil which has a free acidity, expressed as oleic acid, of not more than 0.8 grams per 100 grams.
A bean pod which is still tender rather than one that has reached full maturity.
The Williams' bon chrétien pear, commonly called the Williams pear or the Bartlett pear in the United States and Canada, is the most commonly grown variety of pear in most countries outside Asia.
The most commonly grown variety of pear fruit in most countries outside Asia.
Beef sausage is sausage primarily made of beef.
A tuna steak is a cut of fish from a tuna.
The poblano (Capsicum annuum) is a mild chili pepper originating in the state of Puebla, Mexico. Dried, it is called ancho or chile ancho, from the Spanish word ancho ("wide").
A multicellular eukaryotic heterotrophic organism within the kingdom Animalia.

A bell pepper is a fruits in different colours - including red, yellow, orange, green, white, and purple - from a bell pepper plant cultivar.  Bell peppers are sometimes grouped with less pungent pepper varieties as "sweet peppers".
Golden zucchini is a modern hybrid summer squash (Cucurbita pepo).
A golden or yellow zucchini is a summer squash harvested from the golden zucchini cultivar.
A drupelet berry food product is a product made from aggregated drupelet "berries" such as Raspberries and Blackberries.
A pome fruit of a pear tree.
Pita is a family of yeast-leavened round flatbreads baked from wheat flour, common in the Mediterranean, Middle East, and neighboring areas.
Gai lan is the leaf and stem component of the gai lan plant
A caryopsis fruit of a common wheat plant (Triticum aestivum).
About 95% of wheat produced worldwide is common wheat.
Almond milk is a plant milk manufactured from almonds with a creamy texture and nutty flavor,
A poultry sandwich contains chicken, turkey or other poultry meat.

A burger patty that does not contain meat or any such kind of meat. These burgers may be made from ingredients like beans, especially soybeans and tofu, nuts, grains, seeds or fungi such as mushrooms or mycoprotein.
A food product not including meat and animal tissue products (such as gelatin or animal-derived rennet).
A seed of a peanut plant (Arachis hypogaea).
A traditional Japanese seasoning produced by fermenting soybeans with salt and kōji (the fungus Aspergillus oryzae) and sometimes rice, barley, seaweed or other ingredients.

A fisheries term for several species of demersal fish with fins, particularly Atlantic cod (Gadus morhua), whiting (Merluccius bilinearis), haddock (Melanogrammus aeglefinus), hake (Urophycis), pollock (Pollachius), and others.
An adult female chicken.
A sausage made from turkey meat
A hesperidium fruit of a citrus plant (Citrus).
A genus of plants in the mustard family (Brassicaceae). The members of the genus are informally known as cruciferous vegetables, cabbages, or mustard plants.
A cultivar of dry onion, that has a pure white papery skin and a sweet, mild white flesh.

Food contact materials are materials that are intended to be in contact with food. These can be things that are quite obvious like a glass or a can for soft drinks as well as machinery in a food factory or a coffee machine.
A seed of a ginkgo plant (Ginkgo biloba)
A seed of a common bean plant (Phaseolus vulgaris).
A raceme inflorescence of a broccoli plant(Brassica oleracea var. italica).
A rosette of a cabbage plant (Brassica oleracea var. capitata).
A primary root of a carrot plant (Daucus carota).
A raceme inflorescence of a cauliflower plant (Brassica oleracea var. botrytis).
A primary root of a sugar beet plant (Beta vulgaris subsp. vulgaris).
A caryopsis fruit of a durum wheat plant (Triticum turgidum subsp. durum).
A berry fruit of a grape plant.
A caryopsis fruit of a maize plant  (Zea mays subsp. mays).
A caryopsis fruit of an oat plant (Avena sativa).
